I will continue working to ensure that immigration enforcement follows the law, respects communities, and keeps the focus where it belongs: on genuine threats, in order to protect national security and public safety.

I commend the City of Encinitas for responding swiftly and unanimously after the events of the past week. The City Council voted to launch a bilingual Know Your Rights campaign, to file a Freedom of Information Act request on ICE operations, to examine establishing safe zones at schools and houses of worship, and to demand answers from federal agencies in a public forum. I will do whatever I can to help them achieve these goals. These documented steps show leadership that prioritizes clarity, transparency, and accountability for the people they represent.

Specifically, ICE’s stated mission is to protect national security and public safety. That mission does not justify creating fear in neighborhoods or carrying out operations without transparency. Federal officers should identify themselves in ways that confirm their authority, and the public has a right to expect that clarity. Due process and limits on the use of force are not optional; they are constitutional requirements. I continue to demand that enforcement actions avoid areas near schools and places of worship unless there is no other way to protect public safety.

I am closely following reports of another ICE arrest this morning in Encinitas. If an individual poses a genuine threat to public safety and has a lawful removal order, they can and should be detained and subject to due process. But I continue to have serious concerns.

As more information has continued to emerge, I remain concerned about this enforcement operation. 

This happened along a designated "safe route to school" with students and parents witnessing.

The daughter of the person arrested was rushed over by her mother to say goodbye to her father. Her cousin, a student from the nearby school, watched as her uncle was handcuffed.

Enforcement activities near schools without a compelling safety or national security justification are not in our community’s interest. They cause real harm to children.

I have seen video of an ICE arrest this morning outside an elementary school in Encinitas. The video shows a young daughter visibly distressed by what she witnessed. No child should face that fear, particularly not when being dropped off at school.
 
I have personally urged ICE to stay away from schools and churches unless there is an overwhelming public safety or national security concern. Conducting enforcement at these community institutions is wrong and unacceptable.
 
If ICE believes there was a reason to act near a school, the public deserves a full and immediate explanation. I have reached out to ICE to demand that explanation.

I’ll never stop fighting for veterans.

They deserve care that is accessible, reliable, and built specifically for them. Not gutted to reward donors or advance an agenda. Just the care they were promised and earned.

Unfortunately, this bill passed the House.

I voted no. Not because I oppose veterans’ care. But because this bill puts that care at risk. Our veterans deserve better than budget games and backroom deals.

I’ve spent the last 6+ years in Congress working to strengthen the VA: 
Securing funding for VA hospitals and local clinics. Expanding mental health services. Supporting veterans’ transition to civilian life.

We’ve made progress. But we can’t afford to go backward.

Instead of fixing the system, Republicans are fast-tracking a quiet handoff to private contractors at the expense of the people who served our country.

Once the VA is hollowed out, it’s incredibly hard to rebuild.

And while the VA struggles to meet demand, this bill fails to invest in what really matters:
– Fixing aging VA buildings
– Hiring and retaining qualified staff
– Expanding mental health care
– Ending veteran homelessness

I’ve heard directly from VA employees and veterans across our district.

Morale is low. Wait times are too long. People are burned out and overwhelmed. Cutting tens of thousands of jobs will only make things worse.
And the bill doesn’t stop at shifting funding. It also fails to stop this administration from cutting more than 80,000 VA jobs.

Let me be clear: I fully support giving veterans choices.

If you live far from a VA facility, or you need urgent or specialized care, you should have options. But “choice” should never be used as a backdoor to dismantle the entire VA system.

Their bill shifts billions away from the VA and into private care.

Nearly 75% of the new funding for veterans’ healthcare would go to outside providers. Not the VA hospitals and clinics veterans rely on every day.

Lost in the news this week is that Republicans are once again trying to privatize the VA.

Their new VA budget quietly advances a long-standing plan to gut veterans’ care. Not to help vets, but to enrich their political donors. I’ll fight it every step of the way. 🧵
